The terminology "formula_103-vector" is often encountered to describe multivectors containing elements of only one grade. In higher dimensional space, some such multivectors are not blades (cannot be factored into the exterior product of formula_103 vectors). By way of example, formula_105 in formula_106 cannot be factored; typically, however, such elements of the algebra do not yield to geometric interpretation as objects, although they may represent geometric quantities such as rotations. Only formula_107 and formula_94-vectors are always blades in formula_94-space.
### Grade projection.
Using an orthogonal basis, a graded vector space structure can be established. Elements of the geometric algebra that are scalar multiples of formula_18 are grade-formula_111 blades and are called "scalars". Multivectors that are in the span of formula_112 are grade-formula_18 blades and are the ordinary vectors. Multivectors in the span of formula_114 are grade-formula_115 blades and are the bivectors. This terminology continues through to the last grade of formula_94-vectors. Alternatively, grade-formula_94 blades are called pseudoscalars, grade-formula_118 blades pseudovectors, etc. Many of the elements of the algebra are not graded by this scheme since they are sums of elements of differing grade. Such elements are said to be of "mixed grade". The grading of multivectors is independent of the basis chosen originally.
This is a grading as a vector space, but not as an algebra. Because the product of an formula_61-blade and an formula_120-blade is contained in the span of formula_111 through formula_122-blades, the geometric algebra is a filtered algebra.
A multivector formula_123 may be decomposed with the grade-projection operator formula_124, which outputs the grade-formula_61 portion of formula_123. As a result:
