The decomposition of a multivector formula_123 may also be split into those components that are even and those that are odd:
This is the result of forgetting structure from a formula_138-graded vector space to formula_139-graded vector space. The geometric product respects this coarser grading. Thus in addition to being a formula_139-graded vector space, the geometric algebra is a formula_139-graded algebra or superalgebra.
Restricting to the even part, the product of two even elements is also even. This means that the even multivectors defines an "even subalgebra". The even subalgebra of an formula_94-dimensional geometric algebra is isomorphic (without preserving either filtration or grading) to a full geometric algebra of formula_118 dimensions. Examples include formula_144 and formula_145.
### Representation of subspaces.
Geometric algebra represents subspaces of formula_2 as blades, and so they coexist in the same algebra with vectors from formula_2. A formula_103-dimensional subspace formula_149 of formula_2 is represented by taking an orthogonal basis formula_151 and using the geometric product to form the blade formula_152. There are multiple blades representing formula_149; all those representing formula_149 are scalar multiples of formula_155. These blades can be separated into two sets: positive multiples of formula_155 and negative multiples of formula_155. The positive multiples of formula_155 are said to have "the same orientation" as formula_155, and the negative multiples the "opposite orientation".
Blades are important since geometric operations such as projections, rotations and reflections depend on the factorability via the exterior product that (the restricted class of) formula_94-blades provide but that (the generalized class of) grade-formula_94 multivectors do not when formula_162.
### Unit pseudoscalars.
Unit pseudoscalars are blades that play important roles in GA. A unit pseudoscalar for a non-degenerate subspace formula_149 of formula_2 is a blade that is the product of the members of an orthonormal basis for formula_149. It can be shown that if formula_166 and formula_167 are both unit pseudoscalars for formula_149, then formula_169 and formula_170. If one doesn't choose an orthonormal basis for formula_149, then the Plücker embedding gives a vector in the exterior algebra but only up to scaling. Using the vector space isomorphism between the geometric algebra and exterior algebra, this gives the equivalence class of formula_172 for all formula_173. Orthonormality gets rid of this ambiguity except for the signs above.
Suppose the geometric algebra formula_174 with the familiar positive definite inner product on formula_175 is formed. Given a plane (two-dimensional subspace) of formula_175, one can find an orthonormal basis formula_177 spanning the plane, and thus find a unit pseudoscalar formula_178 representing this plane. The geometric product of any two vectors in the span of formula_179 and formula_180 lies in formula_181, that is, it is the sum of a formula_111-vector and a formula_115-vector.
By the properties of the geometric product, formula_184. The resemblance to the imaginary unit is not incidental: the subspace formula_185 is formula_37-algebra isomorphic to the complex numbers. In this way, a copy of the complex numbers is embedded in the geometric algebra for each two-dimensional subspace of formula_2 on which the quadratic form is definite.
It is sometimes possible to identify the presence of an imaginary unit in a physical equation. Such units arise from one of the many quantities in the real algebra that square to formula_83, and these have geometric significance because of the properties of the algebra and the interaction of its various subspaces.
