There is a general method for rotating a vector involving the formation of a multivector of the form formula_372 that produces a rotation formula_373 in the plane and with the orientation defined by a formula_115-blade formula_375.
Rotors are a generalization of quaternions to formula_94-dimensional spaces.
### Versor.
A formula_103-versor is a multivector that can be expressed as the geometric product of formula_103 invertible vectors. Unit quaternions (originally called versors by Hamilton) may be identified with rotors in 3D space in much the same way as real 2D rotors subsume complex numbers; for the details refer to Dorst.
Some authors use the term “versor product” to refer to the frequently occurring case where an operand is "sandwiched" between operators. The descriptions for rotations and reflections, including their outermorphisms, are examples of such sandwiching. These outermorphisms have a particularly simple algebraic form. Specifically, a mapping of vectors of the form
Since both operators and operand are versors there is potential for alternative examples such as rotating a rotor or reflecting a spinor always provided that some geometrical or physical significance can be attached to such operations.
By the Cartan–Dieudonné theorem we have that every isometry can be given as reflections in hyperplanes and since composed reflections provide rotations then we have that orthogonal transformations are versors.
In group terms, for a real, non-degenerate formula_9, having identified the group formula_382 as the group of all invertible elements of formula_383, Lundholm gives a proof that the "versor group" formula_384 (the set of invertible versors) is equal to the Lipschitz group formula_385 ( Clifford group, although Lundholm deprecates this usage).
### Subgroups of.
Lundholm defines the formula_386, formula_387, and formula_388 subgroups, generated by unit vectors, and in the case of formula_387 and formula_388, only an even number of such vector factors can be present.
Spinors are defined as elements of the even subalgebra of a real GA; an analysis of the GA approach to spinors is given by Francis and Kosowsky.
